text: These days, day to day is shifting all the time as markets continue to be volatile. But you're right. Capital market expectations, by the very nature of them, shouldn't move very wildly. They should be relatively stable. So I spend most of my time asking one simple question. It's what are we missing? What are the models missing? I have this view and all of us, when we develop models, can have a particular affinity for those models and a particular, you can be overconfident about your models. I try to the best of my ability to take the other approach, which is when I build a model, that model in some ways becomes the enemy. And I spend my entire time trying to figure out why that model is garbage and beating it up because the model is going to do what we ask it to do. And it's going to give out those results. So spending time trying to recreate those results are not helpful. What's helpful is figuring out what we're missing. And so I ask to spend a ton of time asking. And I'm not going to give you a whole lot of answers to that question. We're always doing research on what are we missing? How can we improve what we did? We, like many firms in our industry, have lots of software, lots of models, a very large asset allocation infrastructure, which I've always viewed as a living organic system that evolves, it adapts. And so any model we have, we're always asking the question, how can we make that model better? Or what models are we missing that we think we need to deal with the challenges ahead? So that's a lot of what we're doing is research and writing, thinking about outside the models. What can we do that maybe we won't put in the models, right? There's a lot of fundamental things that happen that we just say, look, there's no real way to model it. It doesn't mean it's not important. It doesn't mean that we shouldn't be aware of idiosyncratic events. We talk about them as the best. I can give an example that goes back a few years. But when you think about tensions in the Middle East, what is that going to do to oil prices or commodity prices? It's a simple example. Well, building a war factor is a pretty challenging thing to do, but that doesn't mean that that is a global event. Doesn't have an impact on pricing and asset pricing and risk tolerance and all of those things. So we need to be thinking about all of that stuff, even if the models aren't going to be thinking about it.
